results.name: Number of partitions of n into 3 distinct positive cubes.
comment: In other words, number of solutions to the equation n = x^3 + y^3 + z^3 with x > y > z > 0. - _Antti Karttunen_, Aug 29 2017
link: Antti Karttunen, Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..17073
Index entries for sequences related to sums of cubes
example: For n = 36 there is one solution: 36 = 27 + 8 + 1, thus a(36) = 1.
For n = 1009 there are two solutions: 1009 = 10^3 + 2^3 + 1^3 = 9^3 + 6^3 + 4^3, thus a(1009) = 2. This is also the first point where sequence attains value greater than one.

mathematica: Table[Count[IntegerPartitions[n, {3}], _?(And[UnsameQ @@ #, AllTrue[#, IntegerQ[#^(1/3)] &]] &)], {n, 105}] (* _Michael De Vlieger_, Aug 29 2017 *)
